HOL-9: ES6 Features (cricketapp)

Features of ES6

ES6 (ECMAScript 2015) introduced major upgrades to JavaScript syntax and capabilities
Key features include let/const, arrow functions, classes, destructuring, and the spread/rest operators
Made JavaScript code shorter, more readable, and closer to other modern languages
Forms the foundation of how modern React code is written
Widely supported in all modern browsers and required knowledge for React development

JavaScript let

let declares a variable with block scope, unlike var which is function-scoped
Variables declared with let cannot be redeclared in the same scope
Its value can still be reassigned after declaration
Introduced to fix confusing scoping issues that existed with var
Commonly used for variables expected to change, like loop counters or state values

Differences between var and let

var is function-scoped; let is block-scoped (limited to the nearest { })
var allows redeclaration in the same scope; let does not
var is hoisted and initialized as undefined; let is hoisted but not initialized (temporal dead zone)
var can lead to bugs in loops due to shared scope; let avoids this by creating a new binding each iteration
let is generally the safer, more modern choice for variable declarations

JavaScript const

const declares a variable that cannot be reassigned after its initial value
Like let, it is block-scoped
For objects and arrays declared with const, the reference cannot change, but contents can still be modified
Used for values that should remain constant throughout the program, like configuration or fixed arrays
Helps prevent accidental reassignment bugs in code

ES6 class fundamentals

Classes provide a cleaner syntax for creating objects and defining their behavior
Declared using the class keyword, with a constructor() method to initialize properties
Methods are defined directly inside the class body, without the function keyword
Classes are mainly syntactic sugar over JavaScript's existing prototype-based inheritance
Used in React class components to define state, lifecycle methods, and render logic

ES6 class inheritance

One class can inherit from another using the extends keyword
The child class can call the parent constructor using super()
Inherited classes gain access to the parent class's methods and properties
Commonly seen in React as class MyComponent extends React.Component
Enables code reuse and a clear hierarchy between related classes

ES6 arrow functions

A shorter syntax for writing functions, using => instead of the function keyword
Automatically binds this from the surrounding context, avoiding common this-binding issues
Ideal for short callback functions, like those used inside .map() or .filter()
Can omit { } and return for single-expression functions
Widely used throughout modern React code for filtering, mapping, and event handlers

set(), map()

map() is an array method that transforms each element and returns a new array
Extremely common in React for rendering lists of components from array data
Set is a built-in object that stores only unique values, with no duplicates
Set can be used to remove duplicate entries from an array easily
Both are ES6 features that simplify common data-handling tasks in JavaScript

Using map() method of ES6

.map() was used to loop through the players array and render each one as a list item
Each iteration returns a JSX element based on the current array item
The result is a new array of JSX elements that React can render directly
Requires a key prop on each item to help React track list changes efficiently
Central to how React handles displaying lists of dynamic data

Applying arrow functions of ES6

Arrow functions were used inside .filter() to select players scoring below 70
Their concise syntax made the filtering logic easy to read in a single line
No manual this binding was needed since arrow functions inherit it automatically
Commonly paired with array methods like .map(), .filter(), and .reduce()
Reduced the amount of boilerplate code compared to traditional function syntax

Implementing Destructuring features of ES6

Destructuring lets you unpack values from arrays or objects into separate variables
Used here to split the 11-player array into individual named variables
Skipped elements in an array can be ignored using extra commas (e.g., [first, , third])
Also used with the spread operator (...) to merge two arrays into one
Makes working with structured data shorter and more expressive than manual indexing
